England":"Skelton Castle, Yorkshire, England","England":"England","London, England":"London, England","Whitrigg, Cumberland, England":"Whitrigg, Cumberland, England","Cumberland, England":"Cumberland, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Skelton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Yorkshire): habitational name mainly from Skelton in Cumberland, or any of various places called Skelton in Yorkshire, North Yorkshire, and East Yorkshire. The placenames probably all derive from Old English <i>scelf</i> ‘rock, ledge, shelf’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’, with initial <i>Sk-</i>, instead of <i>Sh-</i>, due to Scandinavian influence. However, in some cases, the first element may be a lost river name, from Old Norse <i>skjallr</i> ‘resounding’; compare   Skelding  . This English surname has been established in Queen's County [Laois], Ireland, since the 16th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Skelding","meanings":["English: habitational name from Skelding (Yorkshire). The place takes its name from the river Skell, itself from Old Norse <i>skjallr</i> ‘resounding’, + Old English <i>denu</i> ‘valley’. In addition, the name may come from Skeldon (Ayrshire), although there is a lack of evidence for a historic presence in this part of Scotland."]},{"name":"Skilton","meanings":["English (Surrey): probably a variant of   Skelton  , though in some cases the name may be a variant of <b>Shilton</b>, a habitational name from Shilton (Warwickshire, Oxfordshire) or Earl Shilton (Leicestershire), from Old English <i>scelf</i>, <i>scylf</i> ‘rock, ledge, shelf’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Greek: the Lord gave graciously; whom Jehovah gave; whom Jehovah bestowed."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":12,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir John de Skelton was born in 1370, in Whitrigg, Cumberland, England, his father, Sir Clement Skelton MP, was 11367 and his mother, Joan Orton, was 25. He married Lady Alice de Ireby on 2 March 1401, in Cumberland, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. He died in February 1439, in Cumberland, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 69."},"et":{"1370–Feb 1439":"1370–veebruar 1439","1370–1439":"1370–1439","1372–1412":"1372–1412","1380–1450":"1380–1450","–1450":"–1450","1372–1439":"1372–1439","1402–1455":"1402–1455","1403–1432":"1403–1432","1345–1399":"1345–1399","1345–1414":"1345–1414","2 March 1401":"2. märts 1401","after  1432":"pärast 1432","1450":"1450","1372":"1372","1382":"1382","1370":"1370","1380":"1380","before September 1369":"enne septembrit 1369","1403":"1403","1414":"1414","1402":"1402","1412":"1412","1345":"1345","1455":"1455","1399":"1399","1432":"1432","about 1402":"umbes 1402","Feb 1439":"veebruar 1439","after 1399":"päras